<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB3BC85D7DFDF9FB2F54CFCA" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="248" pageId="22" pageNumber="247" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB3BC85C7DFDF9FB2F21C8FA" blockId="22.[140,1108,1433,1672]" pageId="22" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3BC85C7DFDF9FB2A43C860" bold="true" box="[185,305,1539,1565]" pageId="22" pageNumber="247">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3BC85C7DFDF9FB2A5EC860" box="[185,300,1539,1565]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="247" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB3BC85C7C7DF9FC2A96C860" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Dyar" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[313,484,1540,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="optima">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3BC85C7C7DF9FC2A96C860" box="[313,484,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="247">Hypotrix optima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a small 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB3BC85C7F13F9FC29C3C860" authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1852" box="[599,689,1540,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3BC85C7F13F9FC29C3C860" box="[599,689,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="247">Hypotrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(forewing length 
<quantity id="4CFC1591BB3BC85C7E30F9FC2882C863" box="[884,1008,1540,1566]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="22" pageNumber="247" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="11.0">11–14 mm</quantity>
) with an unmistakable forewing pattern. Th e mainly orange and gray pattern is dominated by the pale yellow shading around the orbicular spot that forms a flat-bottomed wedge mark between the dark gray reniform and orbicular spots, and the yellow streak at the forewing
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB3AC85D7DC8FF5F2F54CFCA" blockId="23.[140,1108,167,545]" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">
apex. Dark-gray shading in the basal area, on the reniform and orbicular spots, and in the subterminal area gives the forewing a distinctive blotchy look. Th e hindwing is translucent white in both sexes. The 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7CCBFF15296FCF7A" box="[399,541,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">male genitalia</emphasis>
are most similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB3AC85D7E02FF1628C5CF7A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[838,951,237,264]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7E02FF16282ECF7A" box="[838,860,238,263]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7E2CFF1528C5CF7A" box="[872,951,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the valves are more slender and the apical half of the uncus is broad and spatulate. Th e vesica is about 2 × as long as the aedeagus with a tight cluster of cornuti at the base, several scattered spikelike cornuti subbasally, and a cluster of minute spines subapically after a postmedial coil. The 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7DC8FE822A58CFE9" box="[140,298,378,404]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">female genitalia</emphasis>
are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB3AC85D7F5DFE8329F8CFE9" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[537,650,378,404]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trifascia">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7F5DFE83295DCFE9" box="[537,559,379,404]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7F7FFE8229F8CFE9" box="[571,650,378,404]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">trifascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the corpus bursae is curved rather than oval, and the ductus bursae is heavily sclerotized with long medial bulges on both sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB3AC85D7DFDFE382A61CC5C" pageId="23" pageNumber="248" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB3AC85D7DFDFE382A61CC5C" blockId="23.[140,1108,167,545]" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7DFDFE382A98CFA7" bold="true" box="[185,490,448,474]" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7DFDFE382A22CFA7" box="[185,336,448,474]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB3AC85D7CB4FE3929D1CFA7" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Dyar" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[496,675,449,474]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="optima">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB3AC85D7CB4FE3929D1CFA7" box="[496,675,449,474]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">Hypotrix optima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs from southeastern 
<collectingRegion id="49C07696BB3AC85D7E8FFE382F51CFA7" box="[971,1059,448,474]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">Arizona</collectingRegion>
and central 
<collectingRegion id="49C07696BB3AC85D7D9BFE1C2A02CF80" box="[223,368,483,510]" country="United States of America" name="New Mexico" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">New Mexico</collectingRegion>
southward to 
<collectingRegion id="49C07696BB3AC85D7F56FE1B29D2CF80" box="[530,672,483,509]" country="Mexico" name="Distrito Federal" pageId="23" pageNumber="248">Mexico City</collectingRegion>
. Collecting dates range from mid-June to mid-July.
</paragraph>
